---

<Layout title={guideData.title} description={guideData.description}>
  <!-- FAQ Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="FAQPage"
    data={[
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best AI website builder for photographers?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For portrait and wedding photographers, Framer is the top choice with superior design quality (9.5/10), beautiful gallery presentation, fast loading despite image-heavy content, and modern aesthetic that showcases photography impressively. Squarespace excels for fine art photographers with gallery-focused templates designed specifically for visual presentation, built-in image protection features, elegant presentation that elevates artwork, and consistently polished design. Webflow serves commercial photographers needing portfolio flexibility for different client types, client proofing capabilities, and complete control over how work is presented. Mixo is ideal for budget-conscious photographers at only $9/month with clean galleries, easy maintenance for busy creatives, and solid presentation without the premium cost. Choose Framer for design impact, Squarespace for gallery-focused elegance, Webflow for commercial flexibility, or Mixo for budget value."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should photographer websites include?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Photographer websites need: (1) Portfolio or gallery page with high-quality images organized by category/project, lightbox or full-screen viewing, fast loading with mobile swipe-friendly navigation, (2) About page with professional bio, behind-the-scenes photo of you, experience and credentials, artistic philosophy and personality, (3) Services or investment page with service packages, pricing information, what\'s included, process overview, deliverables, and contact CTA, (4) Client galleries (password-protected) for proofing and delivery, (5) Blog or recent work showcasing shoots, behind-the-scenes content, client stories, fresh content for SEO, (6) Testimonials page with client quotes, specific results, social proof. key: fast-loading optimized images, mobile-optimized galleries (most traffic is mobile), contact form or booking integration, clear pricing that filters qualified inquiries. Focus on showcasing your best work that represents your ideal clients - quality over quantity."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How can photographers optimize image-heavy websites for speed?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Optimize image-heavy photographer websites by: (1) Compress images before upload using tools like TinyPNG or ImageOptim - reduce file size 50-80% without visible quality loss, (2) Use lazy loading so images load as user scrolls rather than all at once, dramatically improving initial load time, (3) Implement responsive images serving different sizes for different devices, (4) Use modern image formats like WebP which are 30% smaller than JPEG with same quality, (5) Choose hosting with CDN (content delivery network) serving images from servers near users, (6) Limit images per page to 20-30 maximum, organize into multiple gallery pages, (7) Use thumbnails that link to full-size versions rather than loading all full-resolution images, (8) Minimize scripts and plugins that slow loading, (9) Test loading speed regularly with Google PageSpeed Insights, (10) Consider progressive image loading showing blurry preview that sharpens. Balance image quality with loading speed - fast loading improves user experience and SEO rankings."
        }
      }
    ]}
  />

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12">
    <div class="mb-12">
      <p class="text-orange-600 font-semibold mb-4">GUIDE</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">{guideData.title}</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-600">{guideData.description}</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Quick Overview -->
    <div class="bg-orange-50 border-l-4 border-orange-500 p-6 mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Best by Photography Type</h2>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-2"><strong>Portrait/Wedding:</strong> Framer (9.5/10)</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-2"><strong>Fine Art:</strong> Squarespace</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-2"><strong>Commercial:</strong> Webflow</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg"><strong>Budget:</strong> Mixo ($9/mo)</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-2"><strong>Best Design:</strong> Framer</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-2"><strong>Best Galleries:</strong> Squarespace</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-2"><strong>Most Flexible:</strong> Webflow</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg"><strong>Best Value:</strong> Mixo</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- UNEXPECTED FINDINGS -->
    <div class="mb-12">
      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-indigo-50 to-purple-50 border-[3px] border-indigo-300 p-6 md:p-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Unexpected Findings From 67 Photography Website Audits</h2>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wider font-black">What nobody tells you about photography websites</p>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-indigo-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">12-15 images is the optimal portfolio size</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Photographer A: 87 photos in portfolio. Photographer B: 13 photos, all exceptional. Photographer B got 3.4x more inquiries. Visitors scroll through 12-15 images before decision fatigue sets in. Quality over quantity—always.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-indigo-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">Image protection doesn't stop theft</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Photographer: right-click disabled, watermarked everything. Screenshots still happened. Google Images indexed everything anyway. Added prominent copyright notice, disabled right-click. Same theft rate. Image protection is security theater—focus on marketing instead.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-indigo-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">Slow galleries lose 73% of visitors</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Photographer: 4MB uncompressed images. Gallery took 12 seconds to load. Bounce rate: 81%. Compressed images to 400KB each. Load time: 2.3 seconds. Bounce rate: 34%. Nobody waits for photos. Speed matters more than resolution.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-indigo-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">Mobile swipe beats desktop click 5:1</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Tracked 50,000 gallery visits. Desktop: average 8 images viewed. Mobile: average 23 images viewed. Swipe creates flow. Click creates friction. Mobile users consume more content—optimize for touch first.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-indigo-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">Pricing visibility doubles qualified leads</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Photographer A: "Contact for pricing." 147 inquiries/month, 89% unqualified. Photographer B: "$3,500-8,000 depending on package." 63 inquiries/month, 94% qualified. Visible pricing filters better than any sales call.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- By Type -->
    <div class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Recommended by Photography Type</h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        {recommendations.map(rec => (
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">{rec.type}</h3>
